# Fluff Date: 2026-03-08 18:30:06
<overview>
<p>The Ina-du Swamp Skimmer is a civilian hover support vehicle produced by Hoyle Systems on Zdice, a world defined by the sprawling canal metropolis of Zaniz City. Introduced in 2870, the lightweight ten-ton design was purpose-built to navigate the city's dense network of narrow waterways, serving the taxi and courier trades that thrived among the millions of residents who depended on canal transport. Named from an ancient Cherokee word for snake, the vehicle's slim profile and high acceleration made it well-suited for threading the city's tighter water routes.</p><p>Over the generations the Ina-du became so closely associated with Zaniz City life that it eventually transcended its role as a working vehicle, becoming a cultural fixture celebrated in the biennial Extraordinaire Canal Contest racing circuit and a symbol of the city's commercial identity.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Ina-du Swamp Skimmer is engineered for agility and efficiency in confined urban waterway environments. At ten tons, it achieves a flank speed of 14 movement points using its fuel cell powerplant, making it responsive and quick for a vehicle of its configuration. The fuel cell drive provides efficient operation across 740 kilometers on a single fuel load, well-suited to the continuous service demands of a working taxi fleet. The hoverskirt design allows transit across both open water and low-gradient wet terrain, giving operators flexibility along canal edges and shallow banks.</p><p>The vehicle carries only minimal armor rated to BAR 5 standards, sufficient against incidental collisions and waterway hazards but meaningless in any combat scenario. It mounts no weapons and carries no military-grade systems. This is by design, reflecting Hoyle Systems' purely commercial intent for the platform.</p><p>A precision electronic sensor suite linked to the primary rear steering vanes automatically adjusts small sections of the airskirt in real time, compensating for tight maneuvers and improving handling in the narrow passages typical of Zaniz City's canal grid. The system adds some maintenance complexity but is valued by operators for the gain in responsiveness. Standard configuration accommodates two crew and four passengers in a convertible seating arrangement, with 0.2 tons of cargo capacity available when the passenger layout is configured.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Ina-du Swamp Skimmer operates exclusively in the civilian sector and has never been adapted for military purposes. Its primary operational environment is the canal network of Zaniz City on Zdice, where Hoyle Systems has maintained uninterrupted production since its 2870 introduction. The vehicle is standard equipment across all three of the city's major taxi unions and is widely used for courier, freight, and passenger transport on the waterway grid.</p><p>Its lack of weapons, minimal armor, and passenger-focused configuration make it unsuitable for any role beyond civilian transport. Beyond its working life, the Ina-du also sees competitive use in the biennial Extraordinaire Canal Contest, where strict regulations require all participating vehicles to be drawn from active motor pool assets, ensuring the racing circuit remains a showcase for the production model rather than purpose-built machines.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Hoyle Systems introduced the Ina-du in 2870 to address the growing transportation demands of Zaniz City, a sprawling metropolis of over ten million residents laced with a complex network of canals and waterways. The design entered service quickly, adopted across the three major taxi unions that controlled fares and routes on the city's water grid. Over the following decades Hoyle made few significant changes to the design, maintaining the three-man skimmer's basic configuration while updating internal systems incrementally to reflect available components.</p><p>The hoverskirt was overhauled in 2997, the most significant engineering change in the vehicle's history. The redesign improved the precision airskirt adjustment system and was well-received across the taxi fleets, providing a measurable gain in handling in the tightest sections of the canal grid.</p><p>Competition among the taxi unions for routes and fares grew increasingly contentious through the late twenty-ninth and early thirtieth centuries. By 2999, over four hundred accidents and incidents in a single year reflected how violent that competition had become. After three members of the DeWalt Group died in what union leadership described as accidents, representatives from all three unions met to address the crisis. Their first conference resolved little, but out of those talks emerged the concept of a formal, organized outlet for competition. Jonas Silt proposed the Extraordinaire Canal Contest, a high-speed racing circuit using existing motor pool vehicles on a complex water course through the city.</p><p>The first ECC was held in 3001 over three days, drawing over 300,000 spectators despite initial resistance from the Zaniz City council. The event proved a commercial and cultural success. The ECC Racing Board adopted biennial scheduling, revealing a new eighty-kilometer course for each contest. Recognizing the commercial opportunity, Hoyle Systems developed a customization line for the Ina-du to serve the growing aftermarket. The Zdice Custom Expo grew from this activity, drawing over half a million visitors by 3066 to view accessories and custom show skimmers.</p>
</history>

